      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 24:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of Balaam going ‘to seek for enchantments’. It refers to gathering of signs as the superstitious are wont to do, from this or that, whether they are to do or leave undone any undertaking they contemplate.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "dealt with",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "with them that had",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "familiar spirits",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The Hebrew word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ob",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", usually translated ‘one that hath a familiar spirit’, means originally ‘a bottle’. It is applied first of all to the spirit supposed to reside within the persons so possessed; then to the person himself. After that because the answers were supposed to be derived from the spirits of the dead, it was applied to one called up from the dead. So ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 28:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Saul asks at Endor ‘Divine unto me by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the familiar spirit",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "’. The second use of the word is exemplified in the verse before us, where those that deal with the spirit are called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ob",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the third sense is found in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 29:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " where the voice of an ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ob",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is said to come out of the ground and to whisper out of the dust. The LXX. renders the word by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐγγαστρίμυθος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ventriloquist, probably because the utterances of ventriloquists seem to come from within the speaker without motion of the lips.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The verb rendered ‘deal with’ is literally ‘made’. Hence it has been thought that Manasseh gave offices to such persons as are here spoken of, and appointed (see R.V. marg.) them as official diviners.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "wizards",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The Hebrew word is connected with the verb ‘to know’. Hence ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "wizard",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which implies one who is supposed to be preternaturally ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "wise",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " well represents the word.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 6.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he made his son pass through the fire.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The author of Chronicles says, \"his sons\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 33:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); but this is, perhaps, rhetorical. It was usually the eldest son, who, as the most precious possible offering, was sacrificed to Moloch (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 3:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 16:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and, for the true nature of the sacrifice, see the comment on this latter passage). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And observed times.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " If this translation is right, the reference would be to a superstitious regard for lucky and unlucky days, such as we note in the accounts left of themselves by the Baby-Ionian kings, who begin their buildings \"in a happy month, on an auspicious day\" (see the author's 'Herodotus,' vol. 2. p. 487). But probably the true meaning is, \"he exercised ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "βασκανία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",\" or, \"had regard to the evil eye,\" a common superstition in the East. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And used enchantments.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " A use of spoils is perhaps intended, such as those by which serpents (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "נֶחָשִׁים",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") were charmed (see the comment on Isaiah 47:9). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And dealt with familiar spirits and wizards",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "he placed in office necromancers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (literally, a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "necromancer",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and wizards",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " he gave such persons official positions at his court, instead of putting them to death, as the Law (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 20:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") required - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "he wrought much wickedness in the sight of the Lord, to provoke him to anger",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "he multiplied to work wickedness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " he sought out every possible way; he not only restored all the different kinds of heathen sacrifices and idolatrous customs which had been in use under Ahaz, but carried his opposition to Jehovah a great deal further. As Ewald says ('History of Israel,' vol. 4. p. 208), \"He endeavored to become acquainted with all the heathen religions he could find and introduce them into Judah. For this purpose he sent into the most distant lands where there was any famous cultus, and grudged no pains for his one object.\" 2 Kings 21:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He also offered his son in sacrifice to Moloch, like Ahaz (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 16:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), in the valley of Benhinnom (Chr. cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and practised soothsaying and witchcraft of every kind. On ונחשׁ עונן see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 18:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 19:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", אוב עשׂה, he made, i.e., appointed, put into office, a \"necromancer and wise people\" (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 19:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 18:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]